Developing HR Requirement Analysis And Tender Documents To Procure The Services Of An Implementation Partner For Oracle-Based Human Resources Management Information System
AH Consulting Was Contracted By The Controller And Accountant General’s Department Of The Ministry Of Finance And Economic Planning For This Assignment In Ghana.
Objective of the assignment
The objective of this consultancy assignment is to help the government make an informed decision on the type of human resource database system which is appropriate for evidence-based decision making.
The Scope of the assignment was to produce the following deliverables:
White paper and a presentation on Position Management: 
The consultants will partner with the government’s proposed working group to: 
Collect data and review current state (process, systems and data); 
Conduct 8-10 in-person or group sessions with key stakeholders to understand objectives and key challenges; these sessions will also involve; 
Share best practice knowledge from collective experience regarding Organization Design, and use of Position Management in governments; 
Partner with the PSC and key stakeholders to develop a white paper based on information gathered above and outline findings and provide alternatives; 
Recommend solutions for ensuring establishment controls that meet the objectives, not over-complicated and feasible to maintain over the long run; and 
Make a presentation to the Steering Committee on the key points of the white paper to facilitate policy decision. 

Requirements analysis for HRMIS: 
The consultants will develop requirements analysis document for the HRMIS system. This document will reflect the current requirements of the users, consistent with standard Oracle HRMIS Release 12 functionalities to the extent possible. Requirements which are inconsistent with the standard processes will only be supported if they pertain to a legislative policy decision or there is a compelling reason as determined by a group specifically nominated by PSC and key stakeholders to determine if deviations from standards is needed. This control procedure is an important step that will be instituted by the PSC to ensure standard and consistency of process and data management.  Key aspects of the document, amongst others, will be: 
Master list of HR processes for HR Core Modules; 
Functional requirements for each of these processes; 
Security, roles and authorizations; 
Workflow for data initiation, update, approval and processing in payroll, based on Standard Operating Procedures for HR Master Data Maintenance to be developed by the consultants as part of this document. The SOP will be updated during the implementation; 
Reporting requirements for various stakeholders like PSC, MDAs, CAGD etc; 
Integration with Financials/General Ledger; and 
Volumetrics of HRMIS like number of employees, cost centres, organizations, bank accounts, positions, number of users, organizations where system will be rolled out for direct access to central staff of MDAs and MMDAs, etc, to help the bidders realistically assess the level of effort required to complete the work. 

Procurement documents and evaluation support: 
The consultants will prepare bidding documents for competitive procurement of implementation services partner for Oracle-based HRMIS. Bidding documents will be based on templates provided under the World Bank procurement guidelines. The key input of the consultants, amongst others, will be the evaluation criteria and scoring methodology to evaluate the proposals. 
The consultants will also prepare the evaluation matrix based on bid responses and support the procurement team and the evaluation committee in activities like pre-bid conference (if it is designed in the procurement process), reference checks, final evaluation report, clarifications, award negotiations for the final contract.

